<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-083-222 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 107 955</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  August 12 1991 v13 n32 p47(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The secret history of the IBM PC 'gamble.' (development oforiginal IBM PC in 1981)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Scannell, Ed.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM's development of the original Personal Computer marked adeparture from the company's traditional product-developmentapproach.andP;  Philip 'Don' Estridge persuaded reluctant top managersthat the microcomputer offered enormous potential as a businessmachine and that a development team should be set aside from theIBM bureaucracy.andP;  The original 'Dirty Dozen' engineers assembledto build the PC in Boca Raton, FL created a product code-named'Acorn.' IBM officials in Armonk, NY believed that the Acorn wouldnever amount to much but defended the independence of the project.andO;The company later augmented the group with another from itsBoulder, CO facilities; by the time the Personal Computer wascomplete 50 to 60 engineers had worked on it, often putting in 70-or 80-hour weeks to meet a Dec 1, 1980 deadline to ship aprototype to Microsoft Corp for operating system development.andP;  Onemajor IBM concern was breaking the 64Kbyte addressing capabilitiesimposed by the 8-bit systems of the day.andP;  The PC included aninterrupt controller and direct memory access.andP;  IBM purchased the8080-Microprocessor Development System (MDS) from Intel tomicroprogram the 8088 processor.andP;  The IBM PC was not particularlyremarkable; its basic memory configuration was only 16Kbytesexpandable to 64Kbytes,and it came with a single floppy drive andmonochrome display adapter.andP;  A diskless unit that could beconnected to a television was also available.andP;  Prices ranged from$1,565 to $6,000 for a version with 64Kbytes of RAM,andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   IBM PC (Microcomputer) (History).andO;Topic:     MicrocomputersHistory of ComputingProduct Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Quick bytes: 16 bits of PC industry information. (table)Timeline: the early years. (table)Timeline: the political years. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>